text: Next constituent wants to know why Phillips doesn't see a wall as being part of the immigration reform. Phillips says solution should include "borders in certain places," improvements in technology and more.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Another questioner now asking about federal shutdown and why members of congress got paid when impacted workers did not. Phillips agrees and notes he donated his pay to several charities.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Says he supports state rights but a constitutional convention is a "longer conversation." Jokes about the time. "Unfortunately, it's 7:30. Saved by the bell!" he says.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Missed a few questions here on this feed, but we're onto states rights and money in politics. "I don't like to be labeled politically. There are no issues that are political issues, they're human issues."
author: toreyvanoot

text: Next up is civic training and motivation, esp for young people. Phillips cites support for making Election Day a national holiday, says he wants student government to be enhanced in school. Calls out and high fives his own former teacher in the audience.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Next questions about tax credits for parents of stillborn children, Title X funding.
author: toreyvanoot

text: "I have not made up my mind at all. I am in the process of listening and learning," @RepDeanPhillips says of electoral college debate.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Q2 is on electoral college: @RepDeanPhillips says he thinks it has served the country well, but is conflicted. Says he reveres the constitution but is troubled by popular vote and electoral vote not lining up in recent years. Says time for national convo on issue.
author: toreyvanoot

text: 1st question on DED deadline for Liberians. Says there's "no more important mission" than protecting Liberian community" and is working with WH and colleagues on passing legislation. Says no one should go to sleep wondering if they will be deported the next AM.
author: toreyvanoot

text: .@RepDeanPhillips town hall now underway. Starts off with recap of committees and top priorities, including HR1 and guns. Wearing an orange ribbon given to him by a young supporter in honor of victims of gun violence.

text: 'We need to cause an uproar': Minn. students 'strike' over climate change
author: toreyvanoot

text: Straws and single use plastic have come up several times
author: toreyvanoot

text: Some personal news: a teen asked me which school I go to!!! My day = made!
author: toreyvanoot

text: More scenes and signs from the student climate rally here at the state Capitol
author: toreyvanoot

text: Next speakers getting big cheers for arguments of climate as a racial justice and equality issue. Say climate impacts marginalized communities 1st & hardest. Urge all to not just come out when white friends hurt.
author: toreyvanoot

text: Attention now turning to Enbridge Line 3 project. Young activists have persistently protested and petitioned Walz to fight to halt the project. “It is time to stop building pipelines and move society away from fossil fuels,” student speaker says.
author: toreyvanoot

text: “This is about our future, not their future,” @akhassan_mn says of politicians who say not now on climate
author: toreyvanoot

text: Several electeds here addressing the crowd. All thanking teens for leading the charge: @akhassan_mn: “I’m here to fight with you. I’m here to stand with you.”
author: toreyvanoot

text: Many teens here say they see climate change as an existential threat. It’s already shaping how they approach their lives. Ruthie, a 7th grader, says three friends recently told her they don’t want to have kids because they don’t have faith in the earth’s future.
author: toreyvanoot

text: “This is zero hour!” A student speaker says to cheers
